--- a/aic_btusb/aic_btusb.h
+++ b/aic_btusb/aic_btusb.h
@@ -37,7 +37,7 @@


 #ifdef CONFIG_PLATFORM_UBUNTU
-#define CONFIG_BLUEDROID        1 /* bleuz 0, bluedroid 1 */
+#define CONFIG_BLUEDROID        0 /* bleuz 0, bluedroid 1 */
 #else
 #define CONFIG_BLUEDROID        1 /* bleuz 0, bluedroid 1 */
 #endif

This patch switches the Bluetooth stack from Android's BlueDroid to Linux's
BlueZ on Ubuntu/desktop Linux platforms.

Without this patch, the aic_btusb driver creates a character device
(/dev/rtk_btusb) for the Android BlueDroid stack instead of registering
with the kernel's BlueZ HCI layer. This means standard Linux Bluetooth
tools (bluetoothctl, blueman, etc.) will not see the adapter.

Origin: https://github.com/radxa-pkg/aic8800 (fix-aic_btusb-use-bluez-by-default.patch)

How to apply:
  Find aic_btusb.h in your DKMS source (e.g. /usr/src/aic8800-*/aic_btusb/)
  and change CONFIG_BLUEDROID from 1 to 0 under #ifdef CONFIG_PLATFORM_UBUNTU.
  Then rebuild the module with DKMS.
